00:17:38.630 --> 00:17:40.610 align:middle line:84%
And so that's the first
step-- being aware.

00:17:40.610 --> 00:17:41.410 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:17:41.410 --> 00:17:42.993 align:middle line:84%
I can actually control
this breathing.

00:17:42.993 --> 00:17:43.960 align:middle line:90%
Wow.

00:17:43.960 --> 00:17:46.390 align:middle line:84%
And then you start
explaining to people,

00:17:46.390 --> 00:17:49.030 align:middle line:84%
you have a vagus nerve--
the 10th cranial nerve.

00:17:49.030 --> 00:17:53.470 align:middle line:84%
It sits in your control center
in the back of your neck, so

00:17:53.470 --> 00:17:56.710 align:middle line:90%
to speak, top of the brainstem.

00:17:56.710 --> 00:17:58.510 align:middle line:84%
And it sends out
this nerve, which

00:17:58.510 --> 00:18:00.880 align:middle line:90%
is called the wandering nerve.

00:18:00.880 --> 00:18:02.630 align:middle line:84%
The vagus nerve means
the wandering nerve.

00:18:02.630 --> 00:18:04.130 align:middle line:84%
It's the largest
nerve that we have.

00:18:04.130 --> 00:18:05.870 align:middle line:90%
3 feet long.

00:18:05.870 --> 00:18:07.480 align:middle line:90%
So almost 1 meter.

00:18:07.480 --> 00:18:10.957 align:middle line:84%
And this nerve goes
straight into your heart.

00:18:10.957 --> 00:18:12.040 align:middle line:90%
And it goes to your lungs.

00:18:12.040 --> 00:18:13.957 align:middle line:84%
And it goes, actually,
to all your intestines.

00:18:13.957 --> 00:18:18.415 align:middle line:84%
So from understanding breathing
and that you can actually

00:18:18.415 --> 00:18:21.040 align:middle line:84%
get control of your heart-- this
is what many people don't get,

00:18:21.040 --> 00:18:21.957 align:middle line:90%
especially scientists.

00:18:21.957 --> 00:18:24.190 align:middle line:84%
They're like, but how can
you lower your heart rate?

00:18:24.190 --> 00:18:25.730 align:middle line:84%
And I always ask people,
have you been stressed?

00:18:25.730 --> 00:18:26.290 align:middle line:90%
Sure.

00:18:26.290 --> 00:18:27.190 align:middle line:90%
All the time.

00:18:27.190 --> 00:18:28.000 align:middle line:90%
Can you raise your heart rate?

00:18:28.000 --> 00:18:28.800 align:middle line:90%
Yeah, sure.

00:18:28.800 --> 00:18:30.160 align:middle line:90%
It goes up when I get nervous.

00:18:30.160 --> 00:18:32.870 align:middle line:90%
Do the opposite.

00:18:32.870 --> 00:18:33.800 align:middle line:90%
Lower your heart rate.

00:18:33.800 --> 00:18:34.600 align:middle line:90%
Use your breathing.

00:18:34.600 --> 00:18:37.070 align:middle line:84%
Understand the incredible
power of your mind

00:18:37.070 --> 00:18:39.080 align:middle line:90%
connected with breathwork.

00:18:39.080 --> 00:18:41.870 align:middle line:84%
So when you lower your
heart rate, what happens?

00:18:41.870 --> 00:18:43.070 align:middle line:90%
Blood pressure goes down.

00:18:43.070 --> 00:18:44.120 align:middle line:90%
What happens then?

00:18:44.120 --> 00:18:47.280 align:middle line:84%
Adrenaline production
is minimized.

00:18:47.280 --> 00:18:48.080 align:middle line:90%
What happens then?

00:18:48.080 --> 00:18:51.230 align:middle line:84%
Serotonin, dopamine, all
those other "happy hormones,"

00:18:51.230 --> 00:18:56.770 align:middle line:84%
as I call them, have
more time to be produced.

00:18:56.770 --> 00:18:58.480 align:middle line:90%
And since adrenaline and--

00:18:58.480 --> 00:19:00.260 align:middle line:84%
they are like two
different systems.

00:19:00.260 --> 00:19:02.540 align:middle line:84%
They can't be active
at the same time.

00:19:02.540 --> 00:19:04.380 align:middle line:84%
It's like a dual
system, like a tree.

00:19:04.380 --> 00:19:06.610 align:middle line:84%
So one is the
sympathetic system.

00:19:06.610 --> 00:19:08.960 align:middle line:84%
It's the adrenaline, the
cortisol, the stress.

00:19:08.960 --> 00:19:10.310 align:middle line:90%
It's called fight and flight.

00:19:10.310 --> 00:19:12.373 align:middle line:84%
